Inflation Rises in Europe Due to Food
The accelerating inflation in the euro area is mainly due to the constant rise in food prices.
November’s price growth in 13 eurozone countries was higher than expected, with annual inflation of 3.1 percent registered after 2.6 percent in October, Luxembourg’s Union Statistics Office reported.
The official forecast was only 3 percent, Bloomberg reported.
Unlike the US, UK and Canadian issuance banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not lowered the base interest rate, saying that the reduction, along with rising raw material prices and falling unemployment, would lead to an inflationary spiral.
The ECB would like to keep inflation rates below, but close to, 2%.
According to one analyst, the ECB is in an absurd situation: it has to “deter” inflation so that it doesn’t have to do anything about it later.
In Germany, November inflation is a record 3.3 percent for a 15-year period, rising from 3.6 percent to 4.1 percent in Spain.
Inflation in the euro area has skyrocketed due to soaring food and energy prices.
Wheat futures prices have risen by 88 percent, and the soybean exchange rate has also reached its highest level since 1973.
Similarly, in 2007 it was necessary to pay significantly more for edible oil and dairy products.
The price of oil on world markets has risen by 52 percent this year and last month already cost one barrel of black gold almost $100.
According to the ECB, inflation will jump from 2.1 percent in 2008 to 2.5 percent this year, but it will already fall to 1.9 percent in 2009.
According to analysts, the 12-month inflation level will remain at around 3 percent over the next 3-4 months, but its average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, they expect the ECB to cut interest rates twice during 2008.
