The most expensive is Auchan, almost a fifth more expensive than Tesco
Hypermarkets in the Budapest business triangle maintained last year’s 16% increase in the price level on average, with the difference that there was no VAT increase this year.
Article by Napi Gazdaság
Napi Gazdaság’s usual Christmas basket in the Budapest business triangle grew by an average of 16 percent this year, but in all hypermarkets, the price increased well over a thousand forints.
Since prices in food supermarkets “flyed out” already last December, the percentage did not show a drastic increase due to the previously high base.
But it is certainly unfortunate for consumers that what they could have bought last year for less than nine thousand forints, they will not buy now for ten thousand.
The consumption basket of the Daily Economy in the hypermarkets examined exceeded the psychological limit of ten thousand forints by at least 91 forints.
The highest basket price was 10,573 forints.
(In 2003, the consumer basket cost 6,800 forints.)
The price of Unica and live fish remained almost at last year’s level, but the price of raw breast, nuts and poppy seeds was very high.
The prices of bread and flour corresponded to those of the Central Bureau of Statistics, although in Auchan we found a kilogram of bread even for 139 forints.
The competition did not go below 200 forints.
It was equally surprising in this store that the price of a two-liter Coke in a return bottle was below 200 forints, so even with a deposit, the product cost only 257 forints.
Yet this year, according to the consumer basket of Napi Gazdaság Auchan, it appeared to be the most expensive, while Cora was the cheapest.
According to our calculations, prices in the consumer basket of the daily Napi Gazdaság increased by 15 percent compared to last year’s prices at Christmas, while both Tesco and Auchan increased by about 18 percent.
Compared to last year’s highest and this year’s lowest consumer basket, the difference was 12 percent, while the increase between last year’s lowest and this year’s highest was 21 percent.
In forints, the increase averaged 1,480.
The average price increase last year was 1,206 forints, with prices being affected by VAT growth last Christmas.
It was this process that disrupted trade, and the department stores clearly could not decide how large the price ranges for individual products should be, because they could not predict what the effect of the price change on consumption would be.
(If a trader misplans the speed of circulation of a given product, he may lose a significant profit due to the price range adjusted to the intensity of the circulation.)
Due to VAT, last year's rise in the price of the consumer basket of the Napi Gazdaság newspaper was so extreme that the price of the most expensive basket was 1,720 forints higher than in 2006, while for the cheapest, the price difference was 844 forints.
This year, the most expensive basket now cost 1,630 more forints than last year, and the cheapest one also cost 1,284 forints.
Compared to the two Christmas seasons, prices rose disastrously, and in less than 20 months, hypermarket goods increased their daily consumption by more than 30 percent.
(This, among other things, is not absolutely confirmed by the data of the Central Statistical Office: it has measured price increases in excess of 30 percent over 12 months for several staple foods.
In addition to flour, for example, in the case of eggs.)
In the latter case, however, according to the consumer basket of the Daily Economy, this seems almost impossible, because the price level of the product, which was already quite expensive last year, showed price growth of barely above 10 percent, even in the worst case.
Flour suppliers seem to be in a stronger position than egg suppliers, and they have managed to push through drastic price increases in international chains.
Hypermarkets in the business golden triangle do not complain, they still report on a good year.
In our experience, most customers in the three stores visited are no longer interested in prices.
Everything is bought in quantities, durable food is taken after wages.
On Wednesday morning, all three supermarkets were forming long queues at the checkout desks, as the number of visitors increased sharply.
However, as we know, in the countryside the turnover is lower, several international chains complain to research firms that sales lag behind their plans, not only for food, but also for durable consumer goods.
In many places, they are saved on disinfectants
This year, more than 1,000 cases of infection have been registered in hospitals, mainly due to improper use of antibiotics.
The hygienic conditions of hospitals, overcrowding of beds, and overloading staff are not helping to stop the outbreaks, according to the head of the National Epidemiology Center.
In many places, they are also saved on disinfectants.
Recently, an MRSA infection was diagnosed in the trauma department of St. John's Hospital.
Antibiotic-resistant bacteria have been discovered in a man who got to the hospital after a serious car accident.
The patient was isolated.
A similar infection occurred at the same site earlier this year.
A patient injured in a serious car accident was released home, but not long after he had to return with an MRSA infection, and due to the bacterium found in his body, one important operation could not be performed.
By December 10, 1,094 hospital infections caused by multidrug-resistant disease agents had been reported to the National Nesocomialis Surveillance System, Karolina Boercz, head of the National Epidemiology Center, said.
This means that so many infections caused by multidrug-resistant agents have been registered in hospitals with certainty, the others are unknown.
Nearly two-thirds (683) of infections were caused by MRSA, or methicillin-oxacillin-resistant golden staphylococcus.
The Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria is worn by a third of people in the nose without causing disease.
Infections caused by SA (e.g. cervical inflammation, tonsillitis, skin infections, morning infection) respond well to antibiotics and can be treated well.
However, if antibiotics are given excessively or inappropriately, bacteria that respond well to antibiotics develop into bacteria that are very resistant to antibiotics and that spread rapidly in inadequate hospital conditions.
Especially in case of temporary or permanent malfunction of the immune system in patients with a weakened organism, low body weight or in patients over the years, it can cause serious hospital infections, for example, morning infection or blood poisoning - sepsis.
According to the chief physician of St. John's Hospital, there is nothing special about MRSA infection, similar infections are part of daily practice in hospitals.
"The infection is not to be confused with an epidemic, MRSA is not only there," said Tibor Nyulasi, "where the presence of the causative agent of the disease is not investigated."
Resistant to antibiotics
"We isolate these patients, the nursing staff treat them with rubber gloves and masks and we have the necessary antibiotics to treat them," said Tibor Nyulasi.
Patients admitted to the hospital are first checked to see if MRSA is present, but infection is not always preventable.
Sampling is not in fashion
The vast majority of hospital infections caused by MRSA could have been prevented, but the current conditions in domestic hospitals are not favorable for the prevention and spread of multidrug-resistant disease agents, Karolina Boerczová said.
Because the infection is typically found in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals that receive patients should check and isolate MRSA carriers immediately.
However, microbiology sampling is not fashionable in Hungarian hospitals.
It is also important to note that the National Health Insurance Fund does not fund these examinations.
Most cases are thus revealed if the patient suffers from a perceptible MRSA infection, the chief of the epidemiology center said.
The European Union has strict recommendations for appropriate treatment with antibiotics in the field of human medicine, and there are also domestic guidelines for the treatment of individual infections, medical records.
Antibiotic therapy should be targeted, or microbiological tests should be performed, to prevent drug resistance, but hospitals do not follow this in all cases.
Collections of microbiological samples are even rarer for basic or outpatient treatment of patients, Karolina said.
Saves on disinfectants
According to scientific evidence, MRSA is most commonly spread among patients through medical personnel.
Therefore, hand washing and the use of gloves and masks play a very important role, but even in hospitals there are serious shortcomings.
MRSA is transmitted by droplet infection and touch, but in the conditions of home hospitals it is not always possible to isolate infected patients.
On the contrary, the rooms are often crowded, the beds are often very close to each other, although from an epidemiological point of view, patients should be at least 1.5 meters apart.
Unfortunately, we can also see that hospitals, which are in an unfavourable material situation, are saving on disinfectants, there are few nurses and many patients, which increases the chances of infections.
According to Karolina Burczová, where the necessary protective measures are followed, similar infections are demonstrably fewer or the further spread of the disease agent can be stopped.
Government program against MRSA
Treating MRSA is a huge expense for health insurance companies, which is why it is being fought everywhere.
For example, in England, the government has written a program to prevent MRSA, or to reduce its occurrence.
The program appears to be successful, according to published data, MRSA infections in England are showing a downward trend.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) ranks the prevention of multi-resistant disease agents (including MRSA) or hospital infections caused by these disease agents among its priorities.
The police captain who caused the fatal accident was not drunk.
The official expert opinion in the case of the police captain of the XXII. district, which caused a fatal accident, is ready.
It can be ruled out that the police captain of the XXII. district, who killed a pedestrian on Tuesday and who has since resigned from his post, was driving under the influence of alcohol or narcotics, informed a spokesman of the High State Prosecutor of the capital Attila Morvai on Friday, after the expert opinion of the case was completed.
The expert report confirmed the outcome of the initial investigation, which already stated that the former police captain did not drink any alcohol before getting behind the wheel.
The then director of the police headquarters of the XXII. district collided on Tuesday in Lajos Kossuth street in the XXII. district with his own car while turning a 55-year-old man who entered in front of him while crossing the road outside the marked crossing.
(The latter fact that the pedestrian was crossing off the zebra, moreover, according to the traffic rules is not an extenuating circumstance, the turning car must still give preference.)
After being transported to the hospital, the pedestrian died.
Because of these events, the district police director stepped down and asked to be retired, according to police reports, because he was so shaken by the case.
The case is being investigated by the Budapest Public Prosecutor’s Office.
Attila Morvai also mentioned that the former police captain had been cooperating with prosecutors conducting the investigation from the beginning.
A further 400 million euros for infrastructure
The agreement on three loan frameworks worth a total of EUR 400 million to support education, transport and environmental infrastructure as well as energy was signed in Budapest on Friday by Finance Minister János Veres and Marta Gajecka, Vice-President of the European Investment Bank (EIB).
In 2006, the European Investment Bank (EIB) approved a framework worth EUR 300 million for Hungary’s budget financing of transport and environment projects supported by the Cohesion Fund, with the parties having previously concluded a loan agreement for the amount of EUR 100 million, the agreement now signed relates to the use of the remaining EUR 200 million.
A loan agreement worth EUR 150 million is also used for budget financing of school-related projects.
The EIB has approved a total of EUR 300 million for Hungary for this purpose, the remaining EUR 150 million may be used later, with the extension of the loan agreement.
In the field of innovation, the parties signed a contract for 50 million euros, which the budget will use primarily for the research and development project of Debrecen University.
There was also talk of a 4th metro line.
The parties have agreed that after Hungary has agreed with the EU on the details of the financing of the metro, it will return to whether and how the original contract needs to be modified.
This may happen in the first quarter of 2008, according to János Veres.
The EIB has financed a total of 113 projects in Hungary since 1990.
The interest on loans granted by the EIB with an eight-year waiting period and without a commitment commission shall be linked to the EURIBOR.
Bulgaria is an EU real estate paradise
The development of the Bulgarian real estate market is astonishing - the attention of the whole of Europe turns to the previously somewhat neglected Balkan country.
What, where and who buys in the still cheapest, but fast-rising EU market?
Analysis of the Bulgarian division of Re/Max.
Undoubtedly, Bulgaria is now the most sought-after Eastern European destination for property purchases, with its cheap ski apartments and houses on the seashore.
Of the mountains, the most popular are Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitoša, Albena, Golden Sands, Sunny Beach, the ancient cities of Sozopol and Nesebar, but more and more people are also looking for properties around Kavarna and Balchik.
According to analysts from Re/Max Bulgaria, sooner or later the central part of the country - such as Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, Triavna - will also attract interest from investors and more and more people are buying in the vicinity of the cheap city of Ruse.
The capital city of Sofia also promises attractive opportunities, while business and office space promise the highest return.
Bulgaria is well on its way to becoming one of the most attractive golf paradises in Europe, becoming a popular destination for travel during the summer and winter seasons.
Predictive investors are already buying on a large scale, for example in the vicinity of Bansko.
According to analysts, real estate buyers in Bulgaria are trying to change their lives and lifestyles at the same time.
Most of the customers come from England, but there are also buyers from France, Belgium, Spain and more and more often also from Romania.
Maltese and Cypriot investors are also present, and there are traditionally many Russian customers on the Black Sea and in ski paradises.
Foreign buyers can be divided into three groups, says Georgy Jankov, regional director of Re/Max Bulgaria.
Residents buy either renovated properties worth 50-100 thousand euros, or dilapidated old houses for 5-15 thousand euros, which they then renovate.
They require good accessibility and communication options, the proximity of a large city, shops and, as a rule, a local doctor is important for them.
The second category is chat buyers (Bulgaria ranked among the top 10 German holiday destinations in December).
The third group consists of commercial investors who buy in the hope of a rise in value in the medium or long term.
Property prices in the capital are constantly rising as demand grows.
While Bulgaria has the lowest real estate prices in the European Union, they have risen by 21 percent annually over the past five years.
The rise in house prices far exceeds the rise in wages.
Fodor and Hungarian 6%
Environment and Water Minister Gábor Fodor said the meeting of experts will be concluded on Tuesday and the international conference on the post-2012 climate regime will continue with talks after the official opening on Wednesday.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries are discussing the Bali Roadmap, which addresses the efforts following the Kyoto Protocol's emissions reduction period until 2012.
At the moment, there is a heated debate between developing and developed countries.
The United States has also announced that it now does not want to discuss the exact figures, although it is leaning toward an agreement to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 25-40 percent by 2020 relative to 1990 levels.
Another big issue at the conference is whether developed countries will agree to provide both material and technological assistance to countries that rely on it in addition to reducing emissions.
The agreement was also born on subsidies for developing countries.
The subsidy fund, established by the Kyoto Protocol, will be led by a 16-member Governing Board, most likely under the United Nations’ World Environment Programme (GEF), according to the journal Piac és Profit.
Hungarian 6%
Hungary’s Minister for the Environment and Water, Gábor Fodor, supports the EU’s efforts to maintain its leading role in global climate protection efforts and to help bring about a new international agreement by 2009.
The minister said the EU is committed to reducing greenhouse gas emissions by 20 percent by 2020 compared to 1990 levels, regardless of the success of the post-2012 agreement, and is ready to commit to a 30 percent reduction if other developed regions of the world, or developed countries, are willing to accept responsibilities and commitments appropriate to their capabilities.
Gábor Fodor pointed out that countries that joined the Kyoto Protocol in 1997 had set themselves a target of a 5.2% reduction, with the then 15 EU Member States committing to 8%.
Hungary's commitment is to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 6 percent compared to 1985-87, which our country will meet. - recalls the press release of the Ministry of the Environment.
There is a lot going on in Bali, as an international agreement on long-term climate change policy needs to be adopted within two years, otherwise its entry into force would certainly not be delayed until 2012. In that case, the reduction commitments set out in the Kyoto Protocol would not immediately be followed up by a new emissions reduction system, the necessity of which was also highlighted in the latest report by the UN's International Scientific Panel on Climate Change - the IPCC, which is the winner of the Nobel Peace Prize.
This would delay emissions reductions and inevitably increase the Earth’s average temperature by more than 2 degrees Celsius, which scientists say would have extremely serious and irreversible consequences.
British army recruits on YouTube
British military forces are posting videos of their own actions in Iraq and Afghanistan on a video-sharing server.
First, YouTube was popular with the British Air Force (RAF): special forces operating in Afghanistan since March 2006 are recording videos of actions against the Taliban, the BBC reported.
The recordings, taken by a miniature camera attached to a helmet, are controlled by the Air Force Headquarters controlling combat operations in the Kandahar area and then sent on to London, where they are transmitted to the Internet.
A Political Message is Inevitable
139 recordings of British Air Force soldiers have been uploaded to the Internet, and more than 75,000 people have looked at their "channel".
The British Ministry of Defence registered as "defenceheadquarters" in spring 2007 and publishes recordings of events in both Iraq and Afghanistan, while the British Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Commonwealth Office) and the International Peacekeeping Force in Iraq (MNFI) have their own YouTube channels.
Deployment in Afghanistan
The Air Force has released videos according to their original intent to recruit, and according to the Ministry of Defense, they are also good for acquainting the general public with the real goal of the army's presence abroad.
“The promotion published in this form costs almost nothing compared to traditional TV recruitment ads,” defence expert Gordon Mackenzie told the BBC, “but it also necessarily carries a certain political message, as it confirms in a special way the legitimacy of the military actions decided by the government.”
The Americans made a game.
The army is worried that, in addition to carefully edited, censored recordings, amateur videos are also being uploaded to the server, capturing, for example, the deaths of soldiers: in somewhat hypocritical, "official" promotional films, officers at most talk about losses, but the bloody form of the fight is not shown.
Indeed, many videos from the battlefields of Iraq and Afghanistan have been made available on the Internet, but the British army has only just found them.
Americans recruit a little differently - using a shooting game called America's Army, which is free to download and in which the player can through more or less faithful simulation get directly into the skin of the soldiers.
