It's going on a giant strike
The League of Trade Unions and the National Union of Workers’ Councils (MOSZ) will set up their strike committee on Friday to coordinate Monday’s strike.
A protest public meeting is held on Saturday, and work will be halted on Monday, the day of the final vote on the Health Insurance Act.
The event will certainly cause serious traffic disruptions, as rail traffic will almost completely stop and employees of the Budapest Transport Company (BKV) will also be on strike by 1 p.m.
On Friday afternoon, the League and the National Union of Workers' Councils will present the details of Monday's jointly organized strike.
The League-Mosz strike committee will also be set up to coordinate the event on Monday.
A public protest rally is held on Saturday, with unions joining the strike on Monday halting open-ended work unless an agreement is reached with the government.
This means that no date has been set for the end of the strike, which will begin on the day of the parliamentary vote on the Health Insurance Act.
If the Health Insurance Act is not passed by Parliament, the unions will immediately withdraw the call for a strike.
However, if the legislation is voted on, the strike committees will meet and decide on the next course of action.
It is also possible that the bill on health insurance will be voted on in the late evening or at night, according to the Parliament's Monday agenda.
Due to the start of the strike on Monday, serious traffic interruptions can be expected: work on the railway will be stopped indefinitely, part of Budapest’s public transport can be stopped in the morning, and more than half of Volán’s companies.
At the same time, in many places of the country, the road will also be closed half way.
Numerous trade unions and civil society organisations have joined the strike call, the list of which is constantly updated on the League's website.
Some organizations announced a strike for an indefinite period, others declared a temporary halt to work.
By Thursday afternoon, the Hungarian State Railways (MAV) and the Independent Railway Workers' Union (VDSZSZ) were unable to agree on sufficient services, yet more and more people are travelling by rail at the beginning of the Christmas holidays.
According to the current announcements, the BKV will be on strike until 1 p.m., Budapest Airport from 7 a.m. to 9 a.m., the four-hour strike will be organized by the LIGA trade unions of workers in the energy industry, and the trade union of educators and the Democratic trade union of educators have called for a 2- or 2-hour stop in work.
The Association of Hungarian Doctors will strike alternately across the country, the Democratic Trade Union of Health and Social Workers (EDDSZ), belonging to the Cooperation Forum of Trade Unions (SZEF), is organizing a two-hour warning strike.
The most important of the four demands formulated by the League is for the government to withdraw the health insurance reform proposal and present a new concept for public discussion.
The second requirement is that the new method of counting pensions should be introduced gradually from next year.
The third is to ensure that early retirement for the relevant fields of work can be included in the scheme before 2010.
The fourth reason for the action is that the Independent Union of Railway Workers (VDSZSZ), which is part of the Liga trade union, does not accept the offer of the Ministry of Economy and Transport concerning railway branches, and expects a different offer.
Political Capital: Hungarian Guard Raises Country Risk
The activities of the Hungarian Guard, founded with the support of the Jobbik Magyarországért movement in August this year, have increased the political risk of Hungary and the region in several respects, according to the Risk Analysing Division of the Political Capital Institute.
The company's "risk warning" states: "In connection with the activities of the Hungarian Guard, the greatest political risk is that violent ethnic clashes may also occur in the short term by sharpening the already existing ethnic tensions between the Roma and non-Romani population of Hungary."
The main reason is that the Hungarian Guard's political strategy is probably aimed at provoking such an action - adds the research institute.
As he writes, all of this can be explained by one of the greatest negligences of Hungarian political leaders: "public discussion of the Romani issue was left to representatives of radical and extremist political groups who could build a political strategy on the Romani-Hungarian conflict."
This deepens the problem, makes normal dialogue impossible, strengthens extremists and increases the likelihood of violent conflicts.
In addition, the work of the Hungarian Guard, according to the research institute, was influenced by the great attention of domestic and foreign media "to a large extent spoiled the image of Hungary abroad, especially in terms of faith in the stability of the country and its democratic maturity."
The Institute recalls: as part of the reorganization of Hungarian radical and far-right groups, which has received increasing publicity and vehemence since the autumn of 2006, several organizations have been formed in Hungary since the summer of 2007, calling themselves "national self-defense" associations.
"The common feature of these groupings is that they define themselves as civic associations, while openly proclaiming - even armed - the readiness of their members to perform defensive tasks (in the case of natural disasters, invasion of the homeland, disruption of order), moreover, pointing to the incompetence of the police, the army, or the state," she adds.
He further notes: all this is done in a way that seeks to wrap up the various political efforts built on society’s resistance to politics and parties in civilian garb.
Thus, emphasising civility and the form of association in the case of these groupings not only serves to avoid legal pitfalls of judicial registration, but is also a political strategy.
According to the analysis, the activities of the Hungarian Guard are also an increase in risk from the point of view of neighbourly relations.
“In recent months, they have pointed to the Hungarian Guard as a potential source of danger in several neighbouring countries, while ultra-nationalist political leaders of some neighbouring countries, citing the formation of the Hungarian Guard, want to excuse their own anti-Hungarian policies.
All of this can affect the political stability of the region,” he added.
According to the research institute, the emergence of the Hungarian Guard in Central and Eastern Europe is not a unique phenomenon, so political risks for the region as a whole have increased.
The activity of the Hungarian Guard, he writes, is similar to that of the Bulgarian National Guard, which was announced in August 2007 by the far-right Bulgarian National Union (BNU).
On the background of the creation of the Bulgarian Guard is the mass Romani riots that broke out in one of Sofia's districts (Krasna Poljana).
She used the BNU to establish the Guard, saying the organization's goal was "national self-defense."
For the past 17 years, there has been “gypsy terror” in Bulgaria, but the state has remained inactive and indifferent.
He adds that the initiative has sparked a heated debate among the Bulgarian public.
The increase in the risk of ethnic clashes signals the announcement of some Bulgarian Roma organizations that they will form their own guard as a sign of resistance.
