Holidays are not free everywhere.
In Hungary, the days off are precisely set by law and it has already become common practice to move working days around the holidays, which is less likely to happen next year.
In the European Union and America, holidays are not uniform.
The Hungarian legal system distinguishes national and state holidays and holidays.
Rest days are usually associated with church holidays or important historical events.
We also celebrate the New Year: the last day of the old and the first day of the new year is a working holiday - on New Year's Day, so that people can relax after New Year's Eve.
During the year we have a total of 11 free holidays.
The national holiday is March 15, celebrating the Revolution of 1848, and October 23, commemorating the Revolution of 1956.
On August 20 we celebrate the establishment of the state, May 1 work, November 1 and 2 we remember the deceased relatives and friends.
In addition, the two-day holidays are Easter, Pentecost and Christmas.
Since our national, national, or religious holidays rarely fall on the calendar for the weekend, it has become the practice to move the working day in cases where we would only work one day before or after the holiday.
The price for long weekends, however, is that we stay in the workplace and at school on the previous Saturdays.
The day immediately preceding or following the holiday has been regulated for many years by a special decree issued by the Minister of Labour.
The legislation applies equally to all employers and their employees, to public employees and to persons in the public service.
However, it does not apply to companies and institutions that are in operation without interruption or operate on non-working days with regard to their determination.
This year, the working rules will be changed only around the end of the year: from 24 December, life in the country will almost stop, because according to previous experience, most people will work out the days between Christmas and New Year's Eve in advance or use the saved holidays in this way.
Next year, several of our holidays fall in the middle, respectively, at the end of the week, so the shifts of the working day will be less than this year.
For the first time, the calendar changes around Labor Day so that workers can stay at home for four days at a time.
Saturday 26 April will be a working day, so that Friday 2 May can be a day of rest.
The next shift is related to the 23rd of October: on Saturday, October 18th, work will be done instead of Friday, October 24th.
However, the end of the year next year will be held entirely in the name of holidays, because from December 24 they will have non-stop holidays almost everywhere, even though New Year's Eve falls on Wednesday.
6 Little Things You Can Do to Annoy Your Colleagues
Emails we forget to send, voicemails we never get, innocent lies we barely notice anymore: all of this “diversifies” the workdays of the workplace.
The question is whether you will get used to these minor inconveniences, or put on gloves and avoid unclear situations that can make others angry.
Tips.
"I'm sorry, I forgot to tell you that they were looking for you from the marketing department," a colleague tells you.
You missed a meeting because of that?
At best, he regrets it and tries to fix it, or calls the marketing department and says he forgot to pass the message (this is a less common solution).
Most of the time, it is solved with an apology.
Before making an embarrassing apology, it’s a good idea to think about what you can do to make your colleagues uncomfortable, and consciously try to avoid it.
Do you borrow something that isn’t yours?
There’s nothing more annoying than reaching out for a document, office supplies, or your phone, and they’re not there.
Do you remember putting a stapler on your table last night, but it's gone by morning?
Or have you found a pen on one of your colleagues’ desks that you thought was lost?
Without permission, do not take anything from your colleagues, otherwise they will be right to be angry at you for going through their things.
Don’t take envelopes or sticky notes out of your office, as they can be annoying if you run out of them early, and you’ll need them immediately.
Talk about the private life of your colleagues?
There's no good way to stop the rumors spreading.
Who, with whom, what did he do?
Where and why?
Don’t give everyone your personal information!
When one of them shares his innermost secrets with you, do not abuse his trust!
Lock in what you have heard, and in his absence do not discuss it with your colleagues, even if others know about his things.
Are you reporting your absence for no reason?
If you call the office and report your absence, citing a severe headache, because you are not feeling well, or you think that today you would rather rest, keep in mind that your work, urgent tasks and work, which have a certain deadline, will have to be done for you by someone else.
Take care of your colleagues!
If you know in advance that you will not go to work the next day, or that something may happen that will make you need to stay at home, report it so that your colleagues and managers are not confronted with your absence the next day.
Humming, giggling, phoning
Did you get into a job where you were rudely ripped off by a colleague’s giggles?
Have you inadvertently witnessed a phone conversation that would be better not to hear at all?
Do not disturb your co-workers by humming, chanting, loud talk (over their heads), or stomping, constant swearing, loud discontent.
All this can be distracting even if they are not currently engaged in any project (writing, planning, organization).
Do you blame others for your mistakes?
If something is not on time or you forgot to send an important letter or message, do not blame others for your forgetfulness!
Do not refer to any chaos in the office and noisy colleagues!
Acknowledge if you have made a mistake and someone has paid for it, and make amends!
Ask how you could fix things, correct negligence!
Do you feel at home in the office?
Sweatpants and slippers: comfortable clothes for home, but not suitable for the office!
Don’t wear casual clothing, even if your profession allows it!
Don’t be sloppy, honor your colleagues and yourself by coming to the office in a casual dress - and if your profession demands it, nice and elegant!
