A traitorous broker risked billions on inferiority
Treacherous embezzler.
This is how the French banking giant Société Générale, owner of the domestic Komerční banka, refers to its former employee Jerome Kerviel.
He lost almost 5 billion euros because of it.
But it seems that Kerviel was just a big player who wanted to match his colleagues and certainly not incompetent.
Unlike all major banking houses, he early recognized the crisis in the US mortgage market.
"He's mentally weaker," said his superiors, who sent police after him.
But according to Kerviel’s testimony, published by French media, such as Le Monde, he was the man who made 1.6 billion euros in profits from his business at the end of last year.
Crisis not only in America
"All I wanted was to make money for my bank," he said in a statement.
In the summer, he managed to make half a billion euros from the US crisis.
He saw the opportunity at the beginning of the year.
In February, reports began to surface that so-called sub-prime mortgages, provided to low-income clients or those who have had repayment problems in the past, would have problems.
The whole economy was not affected by this crisis.
Kerviel didn't believe it and bet it right.
At the end of the year, its profits reached 1.6 billion euros.
“When I made my first half-billion, I didn’t know how to announce it,” Kerviel admits, adding that he certainly didn’t keep anything for himself.
Throughout the interrogation, he admits that he falsified the records so they wouldn't come to him.
He even managed to fool the bosses, although Eurex became interested in his trades.
Risk was a profit
Was he afraid he would find out?
I don't think so.
"I thought just the simple fact that I made $1.6 billion for the bank would satisfy them."
Where did he get the will to risk so much?
He had to gradually work his way up to the position.
He joined Société Générale in 2000 just after graduating from the University of Lyon.
His annual salary was around $51,000.
Two years later, he was already an assistant broker, and in 2005 he became a separate broker with an annual salary of $90,000.
He knew he would never earn as much as everyone else.
“As early as my first interview in 2005, I knew they were staring at me.
Because of my education and also because of my professional and personal development," Kerviel told investigators.
But shortly after the start came the first big success.
Allianz made a profit from the London bombings, betting half a billion euros on the decline.
And that was the trigger - he wanted more.
As long as you make money, we'll let you
"It's like a snowball," he told police.
But the bosses knew all about it, or rather suspected it.
"As long as I was making money, they were closing their eyes."
But then came the morning of the beginning of the year.
He lost a billion euros in one day.
After a weekend in mid-January, he wanted to cover it up.
When he came to work on Monday, he was no longer working at the bank.
A few days later, the bank reported that it had lost five billion euros.
And how did they find him?
He became a suspect because of his vacation.
"I've only chosen four days in the past year.
A broker who isn't on leave is a broker who doesn't want anyone to look at his records," Kerviel concluded.
