The most beautiful island in the Caribbean
It is truly an island of freedom.
Whatever you expect from your vacation, it can come true for you if you make the right choice.
Golden and white beaches, high waves, or the sea, calm as a pond.
Palms and all inclusive with waiters offering pizza, ice cream and intoxicating cocktails on the beach.
Kitesurfing, golf and roulette.
On the islands in the Caribbean Sea you will find it in a complete and even richer list.
Only on one island you will find much more, and that island is Cuba, the largest and most beautiful of the Great Antilles.
Under the Spanish, Cuba was the stronghold of their conquest of America.
Columbus described it as the most beautiful place the human eye has ever seen.
Havana became a warehouse and a treasure dump, which the Spaniards looted in America and transported to Europe.
And then came the American era.
Hotel Nacional grew up at the very end of the 1920s.
It was built by one of the bosses of the American mafia Lucky Luciano, because everything that was a crime in the USA (especially during Prohibition) was welcomed and promoted in Cuba by drugs, gambling, prostitution.
Among his guests were.
Winston Churchill, Ava Gardner, Frank Sinatra.
High-rise houses were built in Havana, and cars were used on the wide boulevards, which were among the iconic symbols of the 1950s.
Ernest Hemingway bought a homestead in San Francisco de Paula, just outside Havana, and had his yacht in Cojímar.
On the walls of Bodeguita del Medio were left their signatures stars of show business and politicians from all over America.
What about today?
You can leave your autograph on the walls in Havana’s Bodeguita.
In the bar of the expensive Hotel Nacional you can prepare a cocktail according to your wishes.
And those iconic cars from the 1950s still drive around Havana, because the gills and fiats that were once imported in that salty and humid air have long since rotted away.
Although Havana, especially its oldest part, is very dilapidated, there are not so many beautiful colonial monuments in the area as there.
Other places are also becoming more beautiful, like Trinidad.
Since tourism brings much-needed money, its development is green.
Over the past fifteen years, new hotels have been built not only in Havana, but especially in Varadero, on the coast of Holguín province, as well as on islands such as Cayo Coco, Cayo Guillermo and others.
Cuba offers one more pleasure, which is unique in the world and is especially appreciated by train drivers.
Steam and motor trains carried reeds from large plantations to sugar factories on narrow tracks.
Their fleet has not been renewed for many decades, so there are working machines, whose contours are elsewhere only in museums.
Where to go?
The most famous places most visitors to Cuba do not miss.
There is no need to talk much about Havana or Varadero.
Perhaps just to remind that in the already mentioned Hemingway homestead there is a museum, and who likes this writer should not miss a visit.
Viňales Valley One of the most picturesque corners of Cuba is the Viňales Valley in the west of the island.
The luxuriant vegetation grows out of the limestone bedrock.
Mogotes, limestones and rocks rise steeply from the bottom of the valley and fertile soil takes hold in their cavities, thanks to which even weathered rocks are covered with dense vegetation.
The valley is a place where perhaps the highest quality Cuban tobacco is grown.
Its final form can be seen if you visit one of Havana’s cigar factories.
It may also be interesting for some to know that the Chilean version of Major Zeman was filmed there.
Trinidad
An ancient city that was founded not long after the Spanish colonized the island.
The slave trade and the sugar trade brought him fame and wealth.
Wealth was transformed into the beauty and display of a small town.
Colonial Spanish architecture, greatly influenced by later French settlers, has hardly changed in four centuries.
Trinidad, between the sea and the Escambray Mountains, is a place so remote that it was not until the 1950s that there was a road connecting the region with the rest of the country.
The isolation helped him to stay away.
Nothing was being built there, and therefore nothing was happening, everyone was happy to have a roof over their heads.
If you have more time in Trinidad than one afternoon, then it is worth taking a look at interesting places in the vicinity, such as Playa Ancón, or the Sugar Valley.
In the evening, it is advisable to go to Casa de la Música, which comes to life after dark and the music is silent in the morning.
Baracoa
A small town in the east of Cuba is considered by some to be the most beautiful on the island.
Surely, this view is already influenced by the journey itself.
Both roads leading from Guantánamo have to cross high and rugged mountains and go through nature that has hardly been affected by human activity.
The eastern outpost of Cuba has been declared a World Heritage Site by UNESCO thanks to its intact nature.
They make the best chocolate there, they have the Columbus Cross in the church (in fact, it originated about a hundred years after Columbus' voyage), and from the hill where the former castle stands and today's Hotel El Castillo, you can see several table mountains, the most famous of which is El Yunque.
About coffee, rum, cigars, Sierra Maestra, the Bay of Pigs and the island of Isla de Pinos, the Tropicana cabaret, the shrine of the Cuban patron Caridad del Cobre, santeria, the African religions professed by the descendants of former slaves, many pages could be written about.
But, as they say, better to see once.
Allies in Afghanistan are 'passive', says US
According to the United States, few troops and the lack of necessary equipment affect the course of the mission in Afghanistan.
According to Defense Secretary Robert Gates, NATO should outline a concrete plan for the coming years.
The mission in Afghanistan is not going as planned, the leaders of countries with troops in the southern part of the country agreed in Edinburgh.
In addition to growing resistance from the Taliban, the eight participating states are also discussing other plans and coordination of allies.
While the United States this week, through Secretary of Defense Robert Gates, urged NATO troops to do more, the United Kingdom sees priority in strengthening the authority of the Afghan government and stepping up development assistance.
"Development in Afghanistan is tangible, but military force can only be one part of the solution.
