Government debt rises to $1 trillion in 2009
For every Czech there is a national debt of over 84,000 crowns.
By the end of September, the total debt had risen to CZK 842.7 billion.
The government planned to borrow CZK 159.2 billion this year.
At the beginning of December, however, the ministry reduced the plan to CZK 152.8 billion due to better developments in the state budget.
The state debt of the Czech Republic rose to CZK 842.7 billion at the end of September.
In the nine months of this year, it increased by CZK 40.2 billion.
Since June, however, it has decreased by CZK 13.4 billion.
The Ministry of Finance confirmed today its data on the state debt from the beginning of October.
For every Czech there is a debt of over 84,000 crowns.
Over the past year, the state has been in debt by more than 111 billion crowns.
“For now, it seems that the lower deficit for next year will allow us to exceed the one trillion crown mark only in 2009.
Next year, the debt should be between 900 billion and a trillion crowns," David Marek, an analyst at Patria Finance, told news server iHNed.cz.
Vladimir Pikora, an analyst at Next Finance, said: “We could exceed one trillion in the course of 2009.
When exactly will it depend on the next budget, which we do not yet know.
If it turns out that the situation on the political scene would change, politicians would be willing to save more, it could move to 2010.
I do not expect this change,” he said.
Debts are growing
Government debt consists of central government debts and is mainly caused by the accumulation of government deficits.
Government debt is financed by treasury bills, government bonds, direct loans or loans from the European Investment Bank.
So far this year, the internal debt of the state has risen by 38.5 billion to 719.4 billion crowns.
So far this year, the state’s external debt has risen by CZK 1.7 billion to CZK 123.3 billion.
The so-called negotiable national debt reached CZK 803.3 billion at the end of September and has fallen by CZK 13.7 billion since June.
The average maturity of the national debt increased to 6.5 years.
“Overall debt rose 13 percent year-on-year in the first to third quarters, which is a lot for how the economy is doing.
Interestingly, the increase is generated mainly for bonds, where the increase is 20 percent.
It’s bad that the debt is growing, but on the other hand it shows that there will be something to trade when there is a pension reform,” Pikora said.
Better than expected
The strategy for financing and managing the national debt for 2007 shows that the government planned to borrow CZK 159.2 billion this year.
At the beginning of December, however, the ministry reduced the plan to CZK 152.8 billion due to better developments in the state budget.
The amount consists mainly of the state budget deficit, which is expected to reach CZK 76 billion this year instead of the expected CZK 91.3 billion.
It also includes the planned maximum resources for the Czech Consolidation Agency of CZK 13.3 billion, a ten-billion reserve for the payment of pensions, financing of state bonds for CZK 43 billion and repayment of loans from the European Investment Bank in the amount of CZK 1.8 billion.
A woman is due to appear in court today in Khartoum for giving her name to a teddy bear.
