In the last round of negotiations this Wednesday in Vienna did not reach an agreement on the future status of the province.
Ultimately failure.
Serbs and Kosovo Albanians ended the sixth and final round of talks in Baden, Austria, on Wednesday morning, without being able to overcome differing views on the future status of the separatist province.
"It is regrettable that both sides were unable to reach an agreement on the status," European negotiator Wolfgang Ischinger said during a press conference in Vienna.
His American counterpart, Frank Wisner, stressed that peace in the region is "at stake" and called on Belgrade and Pristina to heed their commitments to keep the peace and be ready for dialogue even after negotiations are over.
"We do not expect violence in the near future, but we are entering a difficult period," he said, adding that "it is clear that the situation is tense".
Negotiations end on December 10
The Troika negotiators, made up of representatives of the European Union, the United States and Russia, will make their final trip to Kosovo on Monday.
The future of the province, where 90 percent of the population is Albanian-speaking, could be revealed in a brighter light as of Dec. 10, when Ischinger, Wisner, and Russian negotiator Alexander Bocan-Charchenko are due to hand over their report to the UN Security Council.
The talks in Baden, near Vienna, represent the sixth and final round of negotiations since the UN mandated the troika to renegotiate in August this year.
Americans and Europeans expect the talks to end on December 10.
On the other hand, the Russians, who have previously blocked Kosovo’s independence from the UN Security Council, insist that negotiations continue beyond this deadline.
“Russia has been and remains in favor of a negotiated, compromise solution,” Bocan-Charchenko said.
Unilateral declaration of independence?
After eight years of governance by the international community, the West sees Kosovo's independence under EU supervision as the only viable solution.
Pristina declares that if the Security Council does not decide in its favour, it is ready to declare independence unilaterally.
Belgrade insists on extended autonomy.
“Unfortunately, we have not reached an agreement,” said Fatmir Sejdiu, president of Kosovo’s self-governing government, in a hotel in Baden, where “last-chance negotiations” have been taking place since Monday.
Hashim Thaci, the former rebel commander of Kosovo Albanians and the province's future prime minister, expressed regret.
However, he added that the autonomy plan presented by Belgrade "belongs to the past that led to the murders and deportations".
"Domino effect"
Serbian President Boris Tadic, on the other hand, believes that a compromise is still under consideration, warning the Albanian majority in Kosovo about the consequences of a possible unilateral declaration of independence of the province.
Belgrade is particularly concerned about the "domino effect" in an area that is still unstable as a result of the wars of independence in the 1990s.
"This does not mean for Serbia," he said, "that a compromise is impossible."
On Tuesday, the Serbian delegation insisted that all decisions belong exclusively to the Security Council, in which its Russian ally has the right of veto.
"Kosovo parliament will have final say"
"For Serbia, only a solution emanating from the Security Council is acceptable," Serbian Prime Minister Vojislav Kostunica said.
“These negotiations took two years.
It must end as it began: on the Security Council floor."
Sedjiu told reporters that "the Kosovo parliament will have the final say on status" and added that if there was a unilateral declaration of independence by Albanian-speaking residents, it would take place "by agreement" with the West.
