Remarkable Space Station Repair
More than seven hours of work in space required astronaut Scott Parazynski and his crew from the International Space Station (ISS) to remarkably repair the torn solar panel necessary for the station's continued scientific activity.
It was a risky spacewalk that set records in terms of duration, distance from residential modules, speed at which it was planned, and the amount of "dwelling" that the astronauts spent to repair it.
The trouble arose on Tuesday while the Discovery astronauts unloaded the Harmony module, a large cylindrical formation designed to install a European and Japanese science laboratory (see box).
This module is a kind of landing strip for modules-laboratories.
We need to be able to supply electricity.
The crew’s second task was to move the 17-gallon solar panel module, which was already on the ISS, to its final location.
After it was relocated, the crew began decomposing the module's 60-foot (67 m) solar panels.
And in this was one of the panels, unfolding like a pulling accordion, due to the clipping of the cable, damaged on an area of almost one meter.
Decomposition has been suspended to prevent further damage to the panel.
The astronauts, who were originally supposed to make a control climb to the Discovery ship, and subsequently go to fix another solar panel whose rotation system had malfunctioned, were forced to attend to the damaged panel.
And it was Scott Parazynski who was chosen to fly to the end of the robotic arm of the ship, added to the arm of the station, and carry out the repair.
He is one of the best "spacewalkers" (spacewalker) of the U.S. Office of Aeronautics and Space (NASA).
Tall, stout, very agile, has a highly developed chest and long arms.
At the age of 46, this original profession of doctor was assigned to "operate" the "injured" solar panel.
After examining the damage in detail, he cut off the faulty cable and fixed some " splints" on the damaged areas.
He was assisted by a second "spacewalker" who remained near the leveling chamber, and also from within, by other astronauts, among them Peggy Witson, the crew commander.
The tools he used, a mini-hockey stick coated with an insulating agent to prevent electroshock on solar panels producing several hundred volts, were invented and "do-it-yourself" by astronauts aboard the station.
After the operation, Scott Parazynski waited until the panel was completely decomposed and then inventoried his tools and returned to the inside of the station.
Yesterday afternoon, the astronauts enjoyed a half-day rest before today, when seven astronauts return to the Discovery ship to return to Earth on Wednesday, as scheduled.
