After the repression surrounding the demonstrations last weekend, former chess world champion Garry Kasparov, sentenced to five days in prison for an illegal demonstration, continues to be banned from visiting, according to his lawyer.
"The Russians have remained the mentality of homo sovietica"
In the background of these parliamentary elections, which are devoid of tense expectations, there are two more open questions:
Who will be Putin’s successor in office?
The official newspaper yesterday published the date of the first round of the presidential election, March 2, 2008; candidates may present themselves to the public until December 23.
Vladimir Putin, elected in 2000 and re-elected in 2004, cannot seek a third term in a row.
However, no follower appears.
What role will Putin play after March?
Will he be Prime Minister?
Or the head of the parliamentary majority and the all-powerful United Russia party, who chooses the government and the president?
Either way, the outgoing ruling power will win outright in parliamentary elections, as well as in presidential elections.
It's a tradition.
"The Russians still have the homo sovietica mentality, they do not feel that they are the masters of their destiny," says sociologist Lev Gudkov, director of the independent center of Levada.
The historian Nikolai Kopossov of the State University of St. Petersburg observes a more distant context: civil society, Christianized in this country five centuries after Europe, has been delayed; the glorious common spirit has delayed the formation of individualism.
After the liberal reforms of the 1990s, "Putin followed a paternalistic model of the state, perfectly accepted by the population, all the more so because this new paternalism was accompanied not by terror, but by a certain economic well-being," believes Maria Lipman of the Carnegie Foundation.
The Russians today "voluntarily give up the personal responsibility" they briefly demonstrated after the collapse of the USSR.
"Why think?"
This phenomenon affects all social strata, including the business world.
Even the bureaucratic elite intend to maintain the status quo: 65 governors (out of a total of 85 heads of Russian regions) run the local lists of the United Russia.
New freedoms taken over from the West are often, as in the 1990s, synonymous with chaos.
Public opinion prefers stability.
In the name of stability, the Russians will not vote for extremists.
Tamara Cherednichenko, 54-year-old professor: "Why think?
Those in power aren't so bad, so why change them?"
Loaded Memory
After more than 60 years in a confidential regime, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which recount the fate of 17.5 million victims of Hitler’s regime, are opening to the public.
47 million archival documents stored over 27 km in Bad Arolsen (Hesse) were previously only accessible for a "humanitarian" purpose, i.e. individually and by name, at the request of the former victim or his/her entitled persons.
The 11 states in charge of the archives - including Germany, France, Israel and the United States - agreed in May to open them to scientists and historians.
As the process of ratification of this agreement by all states is over, the opening up came into effect yesterday.
Sensitive information
Free access by historians to Bad Arolsen will make it possible to examine "in particular the movements of prisoners, the population of camps and the health status of forced labour," explains Reto Meistern, director of these archives managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross (CICR).
Until recently, several states, among them Germany, opposed making these nominal documents available to the public, due to the sensitive nature of some of the information.
What are the presumed homosexuality or mental disabilities of some of the victims of deportation?
The registers of concentration camps or arrest warrants compiled by the Gestapo were gathered after the war for the practical purpose of finding deported or forced labor subjected to civilian citizens, bringing them proof of their internment in order to open the way for their compensation.
Today, more than 300 permanent employees in Bad Arolsen still deal with tens of thousands of individual applications.
However, for part of the scientific community, access to Bad Arolsen is of limited benefit.
“Nothing fundamentally new can be expected from these documents,” said Prof. Wolfgang Benz, director of the Center for the Study of Antisemitism at the Technische Universität in Berlin in 2006.
