Congress Approves MiFID Transposition Effective November 1
In parallel to the parliamentary deliberations that concluded today with a Congressional vote on the amendments incorporated by the Senate into the bill, the government has submitted to a public hearing a regulation that is being developed by the new bill, with the goal that both enter into force before the end of the year.
Representatives of individual parties have consistently praised the efforts of MPs and senators to negotiate and agree on the best standard in order to guarantee the protection of investors and the detailed regulation of the activities of entities needed for the efficient functioning of markets.
The MiFID Directive, which regulates the Securities Trading Act, envisages the modernisation of financial markets while strengthening investor protection, improving the supervisory powers of the State Securities Market Commission (CNMV) and promoting cooperation between the various supervisory bodies of the European Union.
This new regulation will enable the provision of financial advisory services to both specialised firms and natural or legal persons and creates a new type of financial services firms (ESIS), financial advisory firms (AFIs) that join securities companies, securities brokerage offices and portfolio management companies.
In addition, the number of systems for the execution of transactions in financial instruments is expanding, with MTFs and order internalisation systems joining regulated secondary markets to compete with current stockbrokers.
The law also obliges firms providing investment services to disseminate information on key aspects of their business profile, risk exposure and ways of dealing with risk, and requires a statement of all operations performed to simplify supervision by CNMV.
During deliberations on the Congressional Trade Commission, several adjustments were included, among which stand out that securitised receivables should be considered a "complicated" financial instrument due to the high risk to the investor that has been demonstrated by what has occurred in the US with high-risk subprime mortgage debt.
Moreover, the transposition of the directive has been used to legally define the functions that can be held by bachelors in economics and business management 30 years after the Royal Decree was passed in 1977, which outlines the professional functions reserved for economists.
At the same time, the Senate has included the creation of new professions in the financial sector, such as an intermediary who will work externally, will not require permission from CNMV and will be able to provide product trading and client acquisition services for various investment firms at the same time.
