Concerns over new gas dispute between Russia and Ukraine
A dispute is underway between Russia and Ukraine over natural gas prices, increasing the risk that Russian supplies of this fuel to Western Europe may be affected.
Most of the Russian fuel exported to the European Union (EU) is channelled through Ukraine, and any dispute between the two countries is closely monitored.
Kiev has warned that if Moscow raises Ukraine’s gas prices, it will charge Russia higher transit fees.
A previous dispute between the two reduced supplies to EU countries last year.
The latest dispute between Kiev and Moscow comes as the Ukrainian government and Russia’s state-owned gas monopoly, Gazprom, try to agree on how much Ukraine will have to pay for Russian gas in 2008.
Gazprom says it will have to charge Ukraine more, as it has agreed to pay up to 50% more for the gas it receives from neighboring Turkmenistan.
Analysts say it could mean Ukraine will have to pay 40% more for its supplies from Gazprom.
"It is important for us to use our arguments as one of the most important gas transit states during the negotiations," Ukrainian Economy Minister Anatoly Kinach told Reuters.
"The changes in gas prices should undoubtedly be linked to our arguments regarding the amount of transit fees (to Western Europe) through Ukraine."
The last major dispute between Moscow and Kiev caused a reduction in supplies from Gazprom to Ukraine in January 2006.
This caused an overwhelming drop in exports to Western Europe, which sharply raised prices.
Russian gas accounts for a quarter of all gas supplies to the European Union.
Russia has the largest gas reserves in the world, but much of them remain underutilized.
As a result, Gazprom is replenishing its own gas supplies from Turkmenistan and other former Soviet Central Asian republics.
