Venus’ climate may be a glimpse into the future of Earth
Scientists reported yesterday that Venus may have once been a pleasant place to live.
Data from an orbiting European station show that the planet is even more similar to Earth's willful twin than previously thought.
Venus is Earth’s closest planetary neighbor.
These two worlds are roughly the same size and orbit in similar orbits, but Venus is a little closer to the Sun.
Scientists now believe that billions of years ago Venus had conditions similar to those on Earth and could have been habitable.
But the runaway greenhouse effect caused by carbon dioxide, atmospheric erosion by solar radiation, and lower rotational speed have sent Venus on a completely different path of development.
Today the planet is without water, the surface temperature is hot enough to melt lead, and it is ravaged by storms and hurricane-force winds.
The findings from the European Space Agency’s Venus Express spacecraft, which studied the planet for one year, offer a sobering look at how Earth could evolve in the event of catastrophic climate change.
Professor Fred Taylor, from the University of Oxford's Department of Physics and one of the heads of the Venus Express mission, said: "It is becoming increasingly clear why the climate on Venus is so different from that on Earth, even though the planets themselves are quite similar.
"Our new data allows us to construct a scenario in which Venus began as did Earth, possibly with a habitable environment, billions of years ago."
