Mr Giuliani was asked why he had supported the possession of firearms in the past.
John McCain and Mr. Romney discussed whether the technique of simulated heating should be considered torture.
One interviewer asked if the candidates believed every word of the Bible.
Through this, Mr. Giuliani stumbled to the conclusion that although the Bible is his favorite book, he probably does not believe the story of Jonah and the whale.
Another inquirer asked if Jesus would support the death penalty.
Mike Huckabee - who now stands out against all odds in a recent Iowa poll due to his long-standing Christian conservatism - said the death penalty was unpleasant but necessary.
Under pressure to decide whether Jesus would agree, he said that Jesus was too smart to run, making him laugh.
The fight remains unusually open.
Mr. Huckabee's rise in Iowa coincides with recent fundraising successes and Ron Paul's loud cheers at Wednesday's debate.
The two bounced back, as both wings of the party still cannot agree on more familiar and traditional candidates.
In 1980 and 2000, one of the candidates united the party very early and convincingly with the victorious message of American greatness on his lips, winking at both wings of the party.
This time the party is split and the result is far from clear.
Labour's Pain
Gordon Brown once again found a trap he could fall into; his way out remains the same.
Although it is customary in British political scandals, this one is not particularly spicy.
No orders appear to have been sold, no bills in the Paris hotel have been mysteriously paid, no extramarital fingers have been sucked.
But the barricaded Gordon Brown would do without it being discovered that some wealthy businessman for four years had masked the party's ruling Labour party's contributions in the amount of 650,000 pounds ($1.3 million) under other people's names, and that the party had not reported it.
Two months ago, when the prime minister avoided calling an election and insulted the British intelligentsia by claiming that the decision was not influenced by the polls, there was hope of securing a resilient and effective government.
Instead, as the increasingly witty deputy chairman of the Liberal Democrats put it, the once-feared Mr. Brown changed from Stalin to Mr. Bean.
The clumsy rescue of the troubled Northern Rock bank showed weaknesses in management and poor judgment under fire.
Poorly thought-out proposals to change the tax code have brought companies together against the government.
The loss of personal data in 25 million people has exposed unimaginable administrative mismanagement.
The three retired generals started a rebellion in the House of Lords; they protested against cuts in military spending, claiming that being a commander in the armed forces was part-time work.
Now there are many-edged gifts from David Abrahams; Peter Watt, Labour’s secretary general (and their former internal discipline watchdog), has already resigned.
None of this means that Mr. Brown is irrevocably heading towards his end.
Despite this, governments can reach a tipping point beyond which they find governance difficult.
The people don't trust politicians and don't like them, but they usually put aside their mistrust when a new gang takes over.
When it seems clear that a prime minister is unlikely to improve anything, and does not even have to be in office for a long time, this postponement is gone: the state administration is becoming leaky, ministers are starting to make briefings, the press is looking for bad news, and the government is becoming unfocused and defensive.
In one way, Mr. Brown's position is particularly difficult, as he cannot take the position of a new broomstick compared to other political leaders.
As much as he would like to distance himself from Tony Blair, he was his first officer.
For example, the problems with Northern Rock and the records of the tax office are related to the decisions that Mr. Brown made as Secretary of the Treasury.
And although he was not directly involved in Blair's troubles, such as a long investigation into the funding of political parties caused by "ranks for money," voters may well conclude that he was.
Yet Mr. Brown's troubles are not as bad as they seem.
These missteps are not as gruesome as conservatives make them.
As far as Mr Bean is concerned, no one has died or been outright deceived.
And the cure, painful as it may be, is to provide what Mr. Brown’s Stalinist tendencies have always promised: a reliable, solid, and slightly brutal government.
The latest uproar over political gifts is a good example.
Garboid Mr Abrahams, who compares his donations to charity, says he did not wish any publicity for his charity.
That may be true, but it was not his decision.
The laws against the anonymity of big political donors are clear, and they exist for a simple reason: the public has a right to know who could buy access to those who govern the country.
Mr Watt, who said he knew of Mr Abrahams' advance but did not know that it was illegal, will certainly be thoroughly interrogated; so will Jon Mendlesohn, the main Labour money-gatherer who learned of the tricky donations in October.
But so far, Mr. Brown is not involved; there is nothing to suggest that he knew of these schemes, even though the bulk of the payments were made after his arrival in June.
So far, the Prime Minister has done half the work.
He quickly denounced this violation of the law by his own party, but diluted his resolve by reaching for a well-tried instrument, a commission to investigate the matter - moreover, led by a retired bishop and a judge.
In this case, the lessons are not complicated.
If the law has been violated, it is a matter for the police.
In addition, there are other things that Mr Brown has to do, such as find a permanent chair of the Independent Committee on Standards in Public Life, which has had none for six months, and proceed with a real reform of the funding of political parties.
This would require Labour, who are in dire straits, to cooperate with the Conservatives and perhaps even give up their special financial relationship with the unions - bitter pills for a devoted party man like Mr Brown.
But he should face a few simple facts.
The Conservatives now have a solid lead in the polls; he has two years to win back the voters; and the only way to win is unassailable integrity and high competence.
Card sharks
Does the subprime mortgage crisis affect the US credit card market?
When there is blood in the water, the dorsal fins naturally start to flutter around excitedly.
Now that the U.S. real estate market is shrinking, predators have focused on the credit card market there.
Analysts at Goldman Sachs say that credit card losses could reach $99 billion if other consumer loan options become infected with subprime mortgages.
Signs of tension are evident.
There is an increasing number of defaults (with a delay of more than 30 days) and debited accounts (accounts considered unenforceable by the provider).
HSBC said last month it had lost $1.4 billion in the U.S. consumer credit market, also due to insolvent credit card loans.
It is still too early to panic.
Depreciated accounts and inability to pay are still few.
According to Moody’s, the 3.89 percent default rate in the third quarter was almost a full percentage point below average.
Deteriorating rates can be partly explained by technical reasons.
A change in the 2005 U.S. Personal Bankruptcy Act led to a sharp decline in the number of reported bankruptcies that make up a large proportion of credit card losses; the number of reports (and thus the number of write-offs) would therefore rise regardless of whether the general conditions for borrowers have deteriorated.
The industry also shows a good maturity rate, which shows how much consumers pay off their debts each month.
And confidence in secured credit card securities is solid, despite paralysis in other corners of structured finance.
Dennis Moroney of the research firm TowerGroup predicts that their 2007 emissions will be 25% higher than last year.
There are certainly direct ways to spread infection between the subprime mortgage crisis and the credit card market: when property loans dry up, consumers are more likely to go into debt through credit cards.
Credit card issuers, however, look at cash flow rather than the values of collateral items, so falling home prices don’t necessarily mean a change in borrowers’ credibility.
They can even be beneficial to lenders.
The incentive for consumers to repay mortgages decreases when the value of their assets falls below the value of the loan; as a result, the debt on the cards moves up on the list of priorities for repayment.
Card issuers can also respond more quickly and flexibly to more tumultuous conditions than mortgage lenders by changing interest rates or debt limits.
This should, in theory, reduce the risks of a rapid change in the prices of collateral items.
“It’s not like we’re going to rethink all of our loans one fine morning,” said Gary Perlin, chief financial officer at Capital One.
Although the risk of a subprime-style explosion is low, the risk of a gradual weakening is far more real.
If lower home prices and debt reduction push America into recession, the credit card industry will face a darker future.
Watch out for those dorsal fins.
