The three British bankers, who were to be tried for their roles in the fraud linked to Enron's former finance chief Andrew Fastow, changed their story Wednesday and pleaded guilty.
David Bermingham, Giles Darby, and Gary Mulgrew were initially charged with seven counts of fraud when they and Fastow were supposed to participate in financial fraud in 2000 -- enriching themselves at the expense of their employers -- they denied.
