The lawsuit against the bankers -- who earned the nickname "NatWest Three" -- alleges that they came to Houston in 2000 to plot fraud along with Fastow and his former chief aide, Michael Kopper.
Greenwich NatWest invested in Enron’s Fastow-controlled affiliate, which was the architect of a series of Enron scams that pushed Enron spiralling toward bankruptcy.
At the beginning of 2002, the bank rated its stake in this branch zero, but our three Britons knew that it was actually of considerable value.
The company, under Kopper's control, bought the bank's stake in this branch for $1 million.
The incriminated bankers paid Kopper $250,000 for a stake in the company.
According to the indictment, Fastow falsely informed Enron that the energy company would pay $20 million for its stake in Greenwich NatWest.
But the $20 million actually went to the British bankers, Fastow and others.
