Kopper is serving a three-year and one-month sentence at a Texarkana facility.
All three Britons were released on $1 million bail, which ordered them to stay in the United States for an upcoming trial.
Enron, once the country’s seventh-largest company, collapsed into bankruptcy in December 2001 after years of accounting tricks made it impossible to hide billions in debt or report failing speculation as profitable.
The collapse wiped out thousands of jobs, more than $60 billion of market value, and more than $2 billion in pension insurance.
Enron founder Kenneth Lay and former chief executive Jeffrey Skilling were convicted last year for their roles in the company's downfall.
Skilling is serving more than 24 years in prison.
Lay's convictions for conspiracy, fraud, and other charges were dropped after he died of heart disease last year.
