On the waves of oil, money is pouring into the Russian capital just as it did when Dallas had its days.
“We went through the same stage in the 1980s when some Americans got tremendously rich and went to Europe where they were viewed as materialists,” said Marshall Goldman, a fourth-year student at the Davis Center for Russian and Eurasian Studies at Harvard.
Like the Saudi spenders of the 1970s and the Japanese of the 1990s, the Russians are becoming the world's most prominent spenders.
The most exclusive luxury brands are looking for their part in this Klondike.
Elsewhere in Moscow this week, a luxury industry conference attracted Donatella Versace, Tom Ford, and Bernard Arnault, chairman of the LVMH group, to exchange ideas on how to sell expensive goods in markets like Russia’s.
