Venus is Earth's Hell Twin
Despite its life-threatening atmosphere, Venus is more similar to Earth than previously thought. The European Venus Express spacecraft recorded phenomena that occur on Earth in winter: lightning in the atmosphere and wind vortices at the poles.
For nearly three decades, scientists have suspected that Venus is glowing.
Now the European Venus Express spacecraft has produced evidence of electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere, with lightning flying from cloud to cloud at an altitude of about 56 kilometers, according to Nature science magazine Christopher Russel of the University of California, Los Angeles.
According to the well-known theory of the origin of primordial matter, lightning may have created life on Earth. The storms are said to have triggered reactions in the oceans that led to the formation of amino acids, the cornerstones of life.
It wasn’t like that on Venus: “If life ever existed there, it must have been a long time ago,” explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institute in Washington.
Today, there is hardly anything alive on the surface of Venus; the atmosphere is about 100 times denser than on Earth, and sometimes temperatures are around 500 °C.
"Venus may be Earth's hell twin, but he's a twin," Russell said.
Why Venus, which is so similar to Earth in terms of mass and size, began to evolve in a completely different way, is a fundamental question of the Ace mission.
Since no spacecraft has been launched since the early 1990s for the sole purpose of studying Venus, the Venus Express launch in November 2005 was a milestone in the exploration of the planet.
According to scientists, the latest research, which has been published in several articles of the journal Nature, has not only emphasized the uniqueness of Venus in the solar system.
"They have also shown that our neighboring planet is more similar to Earth than previously thought," Esa said.
In addition to the already known winds at the North Pole, scientists have found a cloud vortex at the South Pole that spins much faster.
This phenomenon resembles air currents in the Earth's northern hemisphere, writes a research team led by Guiseppe Piccioni of the Italian Instituto di Astrofisica Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica.
The second innermost planet of our solar system is almost the same mass as Earth, and with a diameter of 12,100 km is almost as large.
This planet, called Morning Star or Evening Star, orbits the Sun in almost 225 days.
However, it rotates much more slowly around its own axis, with one day on Venus lasting 243 days on Earth.
Although Venus does not resemble Earth at a surface temperature of 460°C and a pressure of 92 bar, scientists assume that the two planets formed under very similar conditions.
