He who combines the terms Sweden and wooden boxes does not think of Andy Warhol, but of Ikea.
Or is it?
Wooden boxes currently produced in Sweden cast dark shadows on Warhol's list of works.
Most of his list of ninety-four "Brillo boxes" of the Stockholm type are counterfeits.
After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" a few months ago expressed doubts about the authenticity of Warhol's 1968 "Brillo boxes", comes internal research of the Moderna Museet Museum in Stockholm with the result that brought disillusionment; six "Brillo boxes" donated to the Moderna Museet Museum in 1995 by its former director Pontus Hultén, are copies - like most of the other "Brillo boxes" in the international market of the Stockholm type
Previous events are a tangled, confusing chain of artistic and curatorial events.
Warhol made his first Brillo boxes in New York in 1964, painting wooden boxes that were based on the red-blue-white design of the Brillo soapboxes.
An exhibition of his works in the Moderna Museet in 1968 showed - with Warhol's approval - hundreds of Brillo boxes made of cardboard. These did not come (for financial reasons) from Warhol, but were delivered directly from the Brillo factory.
These were not works of art, but their models, mere exhibition pieces.
Warhol apparently also gave permission in 1968 to make several wooden Brillo cases in Sweden, but they are not on display in the Moderna Museet.
Witnesses at the time now speak of fifteen crates that rightfully entered the art and auction history as authorized originals - "Andy Warhol's Brillo Boxes" with the designation Typ Stockholm.
Some of them were auctioned for more than $100,000.
The problem now is that the legendary director of the museum, Pontus Hultén, later falsely claimed that about a hundred cases had been made and exhibited in Sweden in 1968, which Warhol then handed over to him.
In fact, 105 of Hultén's crates were only made in Malmo for the St. Petersburg exhibition in 1990.
Warhol had been dead for three years.
Lars Bystrom, Chief Conservator of Moderna Museet, examined in addition to the six Brillo boxes that are owned by the museum, also three Brillo boxes from the Swedish private collection, two of which were made in Sweden in 1968 and after their plywood boards had been painted base paint and sanded, they were painted oil white with a brush.
The structure of copies from 1990, on the other hand, showed that the paint was applied directly to the plywood board without the previous primer - in addition, it is acrylic and not oil paint.
"These boxes were not authorized by the artist and should be removed from Warhol's official Brillo box list," said Moderna Museet director, Lars Nittve: "If the Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board in New York does not come to other conclusions, Moderna Museet will have to classify six boxes from its exhibition collections as "exhibition material - copies."
